{"title_page": "Hotel du Cap", "text_new": "[[File:Einfahrt Hotel Du Cap Eden Roc II.jpg|thumb|Entrance to H\u00f4tel du Cap-Eden-Roc]]\nThe '''H\u00f4tel du Cap-Eden-Roc''' is a [[Hotel#Resort hotels|resort hotel]] in [[Antibes]] on the [[French Riviera]]. Built in 1869 as a private mansion, it opened as a hotel in 1887.\n\n==History==\nThe founder of France's ''[[Le Figaro]]'' newspaper, [[Hippolyte de Villemessant]], built the Villa Soleil in 1869 for writers seeking inspiration. In 1887, Italian hotelier Antoine Sella bought the property, and opened the Grand H\u00f4tel du Cap in 1889. In 1914, the Eden Roc pavillon was built 400 yards away from the main hotel. [[Gerald and Sara Murphy]], a young American couple who had expatriated to [[France]] in the 1920s, once rented the hotel for an entire summer, a unique event for the era as the [[French Riviera]] was not a summer destination at the time, but a winter escape for the wealthy. With the Murphys came many writers and artists of the [[Lost Generation]], including [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]] and [[Ernest Hemingway]]. Fitzgerald immortalized it as the H\u00f4tel des Etrangers in ''[[Tender Is the Night]]''. [[Marc Chagall]] made sketches in one of the shady beachside cabanas after their construction in the 1960s.<ref name=\"Splendor on the Riviera\">Christina Passariello (May 26, 2011), [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703421204576329432414615152#ixzz1k7ZFD7Np Splendor on the Riviera] ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''.</ref> The Kennedy family summered here in 1938 when [[John F. Kennedy]] was 21 years old.<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\">Dana Kennedy (May 11, 2014), [http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-secrets-scandal-hollywoods-favorite-701588 Cannes: The Secrets (and Scandal) of Hollywood's Favorite Riviera Hotel] ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''.</ref> Guests included [[Marlene Dietrich]], [[Orson Welles]], the [[Duke of Windsor|Duke and Duchess of Windsor]], [[Winston Churchill]] and [[Charles De Gaulle]].<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\"/> [[Elizabeth Taylor]] and [[Richard Burton]] conducted an affair and honeymooned there. The hotel has traditionally been a particular favourite of film stars, especially during the annual [[Cannes Film Festival]].\n\n[[Rudolf August Oetker]], a German industrialist, and his wife Maja von Malais\u00e9 first spotted the mansion while sailing on the C\u00f4te d'Azur in 1964; they bought the hotel five years later.<ref name=\"Splendor on the Riviera\"/><ref>David de Jong (February 3, 2014), [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-02-03/nazi-forged-fortune-creates-hidden-german-billionaires.html Nazi-Forged Fortune Creates Hidden German Billionaires] ''[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]''.</ref>\n\nSome scenes in the 1986 film,  [[Under the Cherry Moon]],   starring and directed by [[Prince (musician)|Prince]],  were filmed at the hotel.\n\nFor many years the hotel did not accept [[credit cards]]. Cash only was accepted, though most guests wired money ahead of their stay. In 2006 this policy was dropped.\n\nFor about twenty years, [[amfAR, The Foundation for AIDS Research|amfAR]], a nonprofit devoted to AIDS research, has held a charity auction at the H\u00f4tel du Cap-Eden-Roc as part of its annual Cinema Against AIDS event at the Cannes Film Festival.<ref>Rebecca Keegan (May 23, 2013), [http://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/23/entertainment/la-et-mn-cannes-2013-leonardo-dicaprio-space-flight-20130523 Cannes 2013: Leonardo DiCaprio space flight goes for $1.5 million] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> In May 2011, the H\u00f4tel du Cap-Eden Roc was hosting, on its principal driveway to the sea, the Croisi\u00e8re 2011\u20132012 Collection of the [[Chanel]] couture house. It also was the scene for designer [[Karl Lagerfeld]]'s short-film ''The Tale of a Fairy'', featuring actors and models such as [[Anna Mouglalis]], [[Kristen McMenamy]] or [[Baptiste Giabiconi]].\n\n==Amenities==\nThe property is composed of 3 buildings:\n* The H\u00f4tel du Cap\n* The Eden-Roc\n* Les 2 Fontaines\nThe main hotel, a [[Napoleon III style|Napoleon III]] ch\u00e2teau, is located on the southern tip of the [[Cap d'Antibes]] in 22 acres of pine trees and tropical gardens.<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\">Andrea Catherwood (December 4, 2011), [http://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/article-2069851/Cote-DAzur-breaks-Timeless-glamour-Hotel-du-Cap-Eden-Roc.html#ixzz1k7fj1rY0 Eternal chic: A holiday with the jet-set at the Cote D'Azur's iconic Hotel du Cap-Eden-Roc] ''[[Daily Mail]]''.</ref> It houses 117 suites starting at USD $1,300 per night.<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\"/> In addition, there are two private villas, the Villa Eleana (in front of the property) priced at USD $10,000 per night and the Villa Les C\u00e8dres priced at $15,000 per night. Owner Maja Oetker decorates the rooms and suites.<ref name=\"Splendor on the Riviera\"/> In 2011, the hotel underwent a $67 million renovation. Within the complex there are six clay tennis courts, a spa, fitness center, shopping, hair dresser and nine acres of lush greenery. The swimming pool is a heated salt water pool, cut into the edge of the cliff in 1914.<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\"/> Thirty-three [[Cabana (structure)|cabana]]s are located in the rock facing the sea.\n\n==Management==\nThe H\u00f4tel du Cap-Eden-Roc belongs to the [[Oetker Collection]]. The Oetker Collection is managed by the [[Dr. Oetker|Oetker]] family.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040830031403/http://www.edenroc-hotel.fr/ Hotel du Cap-Eden-Roc official site]\n{{Commons category|H\u00f4tel du Cap-Eden-Roc}}\n\n{{coord|43|32|53|N|7|07|14|E|source:kolossus-frwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Hotels in France|Cap]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Antibes]]\n[[Category:Dr. Oetker]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 1870|Cap]]\n[[Category:1870 establishments in France]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Einfahrt Hotel Du Cap Eden Roc II.jpg|thumb|Entrance to H\u00f4tel du Cap-Eden-Roc]]\nThe '''H\u00f4tel du Cap-Eden-Roc''' is a [[Hotel#Resort hotels|resort hotel]] in [[Antibes]] on the [[French Riviera]]. Built in 1869 as a private mansion, it opened as a hotel in 1887.\n\n==History==\nThe founder of France's ''[[Le Figaro]]'' newspaper, [[Hippolyte de Villemessant]], built the Villa Soleil in 1869 for writers seeking inspiration. In 1887, Italian hotelier Antoine Sella bought the property, and opened the Grand H\u00f4tel du Cap in 1889. In 1914, the Eden Roc pavillon was built 400 yards away from the main hotel. [[Gerald and Sara Murphy]], a young American couple who had expatriated to [[France]] in the 1920s, once rented the hotel for an entire summer, a unique event for the era as the [[French Riviera]] was not a summer destination at the time, but a winter escape for the wealthy. With the Murphys came many writers and artists of the [[Lost Generation]], including [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]] and [[Ernest Hemingway]]. Fitzgerald immortalized it as the H\u00f4tel des Etrangers in ''[[Tender Is the Night]]''. [[Marc Chagall]] made sketches in one of the shady beachside cabanas after their construction in the 1960s.<ref name=\"Splendor on the Riviera\">Christina Passariello (May 26, 2011), [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703421204576329432414615152#ixzz1k7ZFD7Np Splendor on the Riviera] ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''.</ref> The Kennedy family summered here in 1938 when [[John F. Kennedy]] was 21 years old.<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\">Dana Kennedy (May 11, 2014), [http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-secrets-scandal-hollywoods-favorite-701588 Cannes: The Secrets (and Scandal) of Hollywood's Favorite Riviera Hotel] ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''.</ref> Guests included [[Marlene Dietrich]], [[Orson Welles]], the [[Duke of Windsor|Duke and Duchess of Windsor]], [[Winston Churchill]] and [[Charles De Gaulle]].<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\"/> [[Elizabeth Taylor]] and [[Richard Burton]] conduc